blobFromImage() function¶

It returns a 4-dimensional array/blob for the input image. You can additionally use it to preprocess your image by scaling, resizing, or normalizing. You can adjust its different parameters to transform your image,

so let’s discuss all its parameters:

image

This is the image that we want to preprocess (for our model)

scalefactor

scale factor basically multiplies (scales) our image channels. And remember that it scales it down by applying 1/scalefactor if a fraction is provided.

size

this is the target size that we want our image to become. Most common CNNs use 224×224 or 229×229. You should resize it to meet your model requirements.

mean

this is the mean subtracting values. You can input a single value or a 3-item tuple for each channel R, G, B. By subtracting from the channels accordingly, this is done to normalize our pixel values.

Note: mean argument utilizes the same units as pixel values.

swapRB

OpenCV by default reads an image in BGR format, but as mentioned above that the mean argument uses RGB order. To avoid any disruption, this function, as the name implies, swaps the red and blue channels. (i.e., why its default value is True).

NMS: Non Max Suppresion¶

if we decrese the confidence percentage, then many boxes will come, the NMS will helps

by usinh IOU technique : Intersection of union

# ---- paths / inputs ----
modelConf= "yolov3-tiny.cfg"
modelweights ="yolov3-tiny.weights"
classesFile = "coco.names"
image       = "dog.jpg"  

# ---- post-process: parse detections, NMS, draw ----
def post_process(frame, outs, img, classes):
    frameHeight = frame.shape[0]
    frameWidth  = frame.shape[1]

    boxes = []
    confidences = []
    classIDs = []

    for out in outs:                         # calling each object boxes
        for detection in out:                # calling each box
            score = detection[5:]            # probabilities for 80 classes
            class_id = np.argmax(score)      # max probability id
            confidence = score[class_id]     # confidence of that class

            if confidence > 0.6:             # keep if conf > 70%
                # YOLO gives normalized cx,cy,w,h  → convert to pixels
                centerX = int(detection[0] * frameWidth)
                centerY = int(detection[1] * frameHeight)
                width   = int(detection[2] * frameWidth)
                height  = int(detection[3] * frameHeight)
                left    = int(centerX - width / 2)
                top     = int(centerY - height / 2)

                classIDs.append(class_id)
                confidences.append(float(confidence))
                boxes.append([left, top, width, height])

    # Non-Max Suppression to remove overlaps
    indexes = cv2.dnn.NMSBoxes(boxes, confidences, 0.5, 0.4)

    font  = cv2.FONT_HERSHEY_SIMPLEX
    color = (255, 0, 0)  # BGR for cv2 drawing

    if len(indexes) > 0:
        for i in np.array(indexes).flatten():
            x, y, w, h = boxes[i]
            label = str(classes[classIDs[i]])
            confi = str(round(confidences[i], 2))
            cv2.rectangle(img, (x, y), (x + w, y + h), color, 2)   # (x,y) = left, top
            cv2.putText(img, f"{label} {confi}", (x, y - 5), font, 0.7, (255, 255, 255), 2)

    # show result (img is RGB already)
    plt.imshow(img)
    plt.axis("off")
    plt.show()

# ---- all at one place ----
def yolo_out(modelConf, modelWeights, classesFile, image):
    net = cv2.dnn.readNetFromDarknet(modelConf, modelWeights)
    with open(classesFile, 'rt') as f:
        classes = f.read().rstrip('\n').split('\n')

    inpWidth  = 416
    inpHeight = 416

    frame = cv2.imread(image)
    img   = cv2.cvtColor(frame, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB)  # for matplotlib display

    # create blob (as in your screenshot)
    blob = cv2.dnn.blobFromImage(frame, 1/255, (inpWidth, inpHeight), [0,0,0], 1, crop=False)
    net.setInput(blob)

    yolo_layers = net.getUnconnectedOutLayersNames()
    outs = net.forward(yolo_layers)

    post_process(frame, outs, img, classes)

# ---- run ----
yolo_out(modelConf, modelweights, classesFile, image)
